  "response": "Pubic and body hair growth is controlled by several factors, and it stops growing after reaching a certain length due to the natural hair growth cycle. Here's a breakdown:\n\n1. Hair Growth Cycle\n- Anagen (growth) phase\n- Catagen (transition) phase\n- Telogen (resting) phase\n\n2. Predetermined Length\nEach hair follicle has a genetically predetermined maximum length, which varies by body location. This is due to:\n- Hormonal influences\n- Genetic factors\n- Individual hair follicle characteristics\n\n3. Programmed Duration\n- Hair follicles are programmed to grow for a specific duration\n- Once this time is complete, the hair falls out and a new hair begins growing\n\n4. Hormonal Regulation\n- Androgens (like testosterone) influence hair growth\n- Different body areas respond differently to hormonal signals\n\n5. Limiting Factors\n- Hair follicle size\n- Hair thickness\n- Genetic predisposition\n- Hormonal balance\n\nThis is why body hair tends to have a shorter maximum length compared to scalp hair, which can grow much longer before falling out.\n\nThe process ensures that hair is replaced periodically and maintains a relatively consistent length across different body areas.",
